Chicago TNC Data

Morteza Taiebat

Ridesourcing Trip Data from City of Chicago

Data comes from the ridehailing trip records on the City of Chicagos open data portal. Ridehailing data is available through Dec 31, 2019 now but regularly updates (Q1 2020 is delayed.) Each trip record comes with 21 variables. Pick up and drop off are record in the Census Tract (with GPS coordinates). Census Tracts are suppressed in some cases, and times are rounded to the nearest 15 minutes (while trip seconds are accurate). Fares are rounded to the nearest $2.50 and tips are rounded to the nearest 1.00.

I use the American Community Survey 20142018 5-year estimates data (specifically 2018 adjustments) for each census tract whenever I need socioeconomic and demographic variables.

require(tidycensus)

Manipulate Timestamps

I use the package lubridate to transform the timestamps. Then extract the date and time of start for each trip. I also find the week day of each trip in order to use for aggregate analysis (reorder the factors so the week starts on Monday). Finally, I remove the original timestamps to reduce the size dataset.

data$start <- parse_date_time(data$Trip.Start.Timestamp, "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")
data$end <- parse_date_time(data$Trip.End.Timestamp, "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")
# Alternative timestamp transformartion 
# data$start <- as.POSIXct(data$Trip.Start.Timestamp, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")

data$start.date <- as.Date(data$start, format = "%Y-%m-%d  %H:%M:%S")
data$start.time <- format(as.POSIXct(strptime(data$start, 
                                               "%Y-%m-%d  %H:%M:%S",tz="")),
                          format = "%H:%M")
data$start.time <- as.POSIXct(data$start.time, format = "%H:%M")
str(data$start.time)
# find week day
data$start.day <- wday(data$start.date, label = T) # we use labels=true here to return day labels instead of numeric values. 
data$start.day <- factor(data$start.day, levels = c("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun"))

# manipulate end time
data$end.date <- as.Date(data$end, format = "%Y-%m-%d  %H:%M:%S")
data$end.time <- format(as.POSIXct(strptime(data$end, 
                                              "%Y-%m-%d  %H:%M:%S",tz="")) ,
                          format = "%H:%M")
data$end.time <- as.POSIXct(data$end.time, format = "%H:%M")

## remove start dates on 12/1/2019
data<-data %>% 
  filter(start < as.Date("2019-12-01")) %>% 
  select(-c("Trip.End.Timestamp", "Trip.Start.Timestamp"))

Data Cleaning Procedure

The data include instance of missing values and incorrect observations. I attempt to clean the dataset through these iterative steps: * remove trips with total trip time less than 1 minutes and longer than 5 hours * remove trips less total distance traveled than 0.25 miles and greater than 300 miles * remove trips with total fare equal to zero (fares are already rounded) * remove trips with extreme speeds (below 0.2 mph and above 80 mph)

I also create a new variable to whether the trip was pooled or not: pooled This variable is zero for solo trips and 1 for any number of shares. Please note that the traveler could authorize a shared trip but no matching could be made through the trip (variable Shared.Trip.Authorized could be true or false).

Finally I save the cleaned dataset for ease of future use:

data <- data %>%
  filter( Trip.Seconds < 5*3600, Trip.Seconds > 60) %>% # remove trips less than 60 secs or 5 hours
  filter(Trip.Miles < 300 , Trip.Miles > 0.25 ) %>%  # remove trips with extreme or zero miles
  filter(Trip.Total > 0) %>% # trip total greater than zero
  filter(Trip.Miles/(Trip.Seconds/3600) < 80,
         Trip.Miles/(Trip.Seconds/3600) > 0.2) # remove trips with extreme speeds

summary(data$Trip.Miles/(data$Trip.Seconds/3600))

data <- data %>% mutate("pooled" = ifelse(Trips.Pooled > 1, yes = 1, no = 0)) # mutate a column to show whether the trip was pooled or not

save(data, file = "TNC_Trips_data_clean.RData")

The cleaned dataset has the record of 9,270,476 trips with 28 variables. * Note some trips may start and/or end out of the census tracts of the City of Chicago. This observations do not have a record of start and end location. For now, I do not remove them but in extraction of O-D pairs, they will be removed.

Reduced Tracts

The Cook county has 518 census tracts more than the city of Chicago, so using the Cook country maps would result in unnecessarily large maps. Using the info from City of Chicago Data Portal, I filter only census tracts inside the boundary of city.

chicago_tracts <- read.csv("CensusTractsTIGER2010.csv")
needed<-which(chicago$GEOID %in% chicago_tracts$GEOID10)    
chicago <- chicago[needed,]

With this reduced map, I will lose nearly 200 tracts with pick ups and drop offs. However, upon a closer look, these tracts have very low density of pick up and drop offs. Note that I keep all tracts in the analysis but to make the maps clearer, I remove them from mapping.

Origin-Destination Analysis

Since all trips are recorded as trip OD in census tracts, I can extract all OD pairs. I calculate the total number of trip between OD pairs and then find longitude and latitude for visualization. after extraction, I find 223,424 OD pairs. However, many of these OD pairs had only a few trips during Nov 2019. So I choose to remove OD pairs with less than 5 trips for visualization:

require(ggspatial)

ODPAIRS <- data %>% 
  group_by(Pickup.Census.Tract, Dropoff.Census.Tract) %>% 
  summarise("pick.long" = median(Pickup.Centroid.Longitude, na.rm = T), 
            "pick.lat" = median(Pickup.Centroid.Latitude, na.rm = T),
            "drop.long" = median(Dropoff.Centroid.Longitude, na.rm = T), 
            "drop.lat" = median(Dropoff.Centroid.Latitude, na.rm = T),
            "sum.trip" = n())%>% 
  filter(sum.trip > 5) %>% # exclude ODs with less than 5 trip in Nov 2019
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(!(Pickup.Census.Tract ==  Dropoff.Census.Tract)) %>% # remove OD in the same tract
  drop_na()



chicago %>%   ggplot() + geom_sf(color = "grey", fill = NA,  size = 0.1) +
  geom_curve(data = ODPAIRS, aes(x = pick.long, y = pick.lat, 
                                   xend = drop.long, yend = drop.lat), size = 0.05, alpha = 0.05, color = "blue",  curvature = -0.2) + 
  annotation_north_arrow(location = "bl", which_north = "true",
                         height = unit(1, "cm"), width = unit(1, "cm"),
                         pad_x = unit(0.5, "cm"), pad_y = unit(1, "cm"),
                         style = north_arrow_fancy_orienteering) +
  annotation_scale(location = "bl", width_hint = 0.25) + theme_void() +
  coord_sf(xlim = c(-87.95, -87.5), ylim = c(41.65, 42.01), expand = T)

The above figure shows the network of trips among 83,938 OD pairs in Nov 2019.

Travel Impedance

Travel impedance measures are the variables that are resisting the travel ability. In general, trip fare, trip distance and trip duration are considered as main travel impedances. I consider the median and standard deviation of these variables to capture the variations in rider characteristics (riders who select different types of ridesourcing service, i.e., UberPool versus UberX), price fluctuations (e.g., surge pricing), traffic condition, route choice, etc. The median is chosen instead of mean to be robust to outlier while also measure the characteristics of a regular trip. Lets take a look at the travel impedance:

impedance <- data %>% 
  group_by(Pickup.Census.Tract, Dropoff.Census.Tract) %>% 
  summarise("sum.trip" = n(),
            "trip.fare.median" = median(Fare, na.rm = T),
            "trip.distance.median" = median(Trip.Miles, na.rm = T),
            "trip.time.median" = median(Trip.Seconds/60, na.rm = T),
            "trip.fare.sd" = sd(Fare, na.rm = T),
            "trip.distance.sd" = sd(Trip.Miles, na.rm = T),
            "trip.time.sd" = sd(Trip.Seconds/60, na.rm = T))%>% 
  filter(sum.trip > 5) %>% # exclude ODs with less than 5 trip in Nov 2019
  ungroup() %>% 
  drop_na()

Equity In Chicago

Using the definition of Dissimilarity and Isolation by Culter et al. (1999) we look at the spatial equity in Chicago:

Cutler, David M., Edward L. Glaeser, and Jacob L. Vigdor. The rise and decline of the American ghetto. Journal of political economy 107.3 (1999): 455-506.

Focusing on the African Americans, the plot here shows the dissimilarity index in each tract. The next plot shows the population of African Americans to the total population of the tract. Unsurprisingly, the correlation of dissimilarity and the population of African Americans is around 89%

# Total population by tract
chicago <- get_acs(geography = "tract", 
                   variables = c("B01001_001") , 
                   state = "IL", 
                   county = c("Cook"), 
                   geometry = TRUE)
## Getting data from the 2014-2018 5-year ACS
#AA population by tract
chicago1 <- get_acs(geography = "tract", 
                   variables = c("B02009_001") , 
                   state = "IL", 
                   county = c("Cook"), 
                   geometry = TRUE)
## Getting data from the 2014-2018 5-year ACS
chicago$AA <- chicago1$estimate
remove(chicago1)

#Proportion of AA
chicago$prop_AA<- chicago$AA/sum(chicago$AA)

#Proportion of non AA
chicago$prop_AAc <- chicago$estimate - chicago$AA
chicago$prop_AAc <- chicago$prop_AAc/sum(chicago$prop_AAc)

#Proportion of AA to popultion of tract
chicago$prop_AA_all <- chicago$AA/chicago$estimate


#Dissimilarity
chicago$dissimilarity <- chicago$prop_AA - chicago$prop_AAc


#Isolation Index
chicago$prop_AA_t <- chicago$AA / chicago$estimate

prop_AA_city <- sum(chicago$AA)/sum(chicago$estimate)
prop_AA_city
## [1] 0.2452404
indices<-data.frame(index=factor(c("Dissimilarity", "Isolation")), value=rep(NA,2))

indices$value[indices$index=="Dissimilarity"]<-0.5*sum(abs(chicago$dissimilarity))
indices$value[indices$index=="Isolation"]<-(sum(chicago$prop_AA * chicago$prop_AA_t, na.rm = T) - prop_AA_city)/(1-prop_AA_city)
